By Ma Suping and Cui Huiying, special correspondent, southern weekend

Editor in chief | Cao Haidong

Yang Fang's life depends on whether a flexible tube can be inserted smoothly into her throat.

Pushing sedatives and muscle relaxants, Yang Fang, a 67-year-old woman whose consciousness had become blurred, fell into a lethargic state and slowly calmed down. The window from injection to spontaneous inhalation is 90 seconds -- including 60 seconds for the anesthetic to kick in.

To Protect Lips, a visual laryngoscope opens the mouth and throat. "Can you see it? " "Yes. " In a short reply, the anesthesiologist promptly handed over a hose about 22 centimeters long and 8 millimeters in diameter. At this point, the anesthesiologist's eyes are opposite Yang Fang's mouth and nose, see the opening of the Trachea, the hose can be placed inside the trachea.

The tube was inserted through the mouth, into the glottis, and into the trachea. Within 30 seconds, Yang's airway opened, and the Lung Aerosol rushed straight out, reaching the anesthesiologist's positive pressure head cap -- a form of close airway contact, the highest risk for infection among health care workers.

Yang's doctor, Liu Yongjun, breathed a sigh of relief as sunlight streamed through the glass windows and the patient's various functions signaled rhythmically through the ticking of the monitors. The day was the 10th for Liu Yongjun, deputy director of the Department of Critical Care Medicine at the Wuhan Union Hospital, National Sun Yat-sen University.

He remembers that when Yang Fang first came in with a nasal tube, the Oxygenation (the concentration of oxygen in the blood and the parameters of the patient's breathing cycle) was in the low 80s, well below the 93 percent pass mark. It was 7:00 p.m. on February 8th.

The patient was stable for three days after wearing a non-invasive breathing mask. But after three days, if you take off your oxygen mask, even if you have a drink of water or a meal, the Oxygenation will rub against you and come down. Gravity "crushes" the Alveoli at the bottom. In order to open the Alveoli and drain and expel Phlegm, the heavily armed nurses had to turn her over, turning her into a prone position during the day and back again at night.

"It's too early to talk about getting out of danger. " The day after the INTUBATION, Yang Fang's condition is still unchanged. Kidney failure, elevated Troponin (a marker of myocardial damage) , falling blood pressure... signs of organ failure appear in turn.

For Liu, this is not the first time he has faced danger, and it will not be the last. To be or not to be, in Wuhan in 2020, there are only a few minutes, sometimes even depending on the availability of an oxygen line.

About 10%-20% of patients with NCP develop severe symptoms —————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— --. In severe cases, a small number of patients develop a crisis condition called Florida that requires breathing to keep the airway open, some go into shock, and others go into organ failure.

In fact, since February 9, a large number of patients who were previously unable to be admitted but were delayed have been transferred to intensive care designated hospitals, with reduced outpatient pressure and increasingly heavy air in the intensive care units.

As of Feb. 25, the number of severe cases outside Hubei Province, Wuhan, and Hubei provinces was as high as 8326,7355,426. At the beginning of February, the case fatality rate in Wuhan was estimated to be 30 times higher than the overall level outside Hubei. Race Against Death to save the critically ill and become the True Crime of the moment.

1
36 critical care patients, 17 of them

1

###36 critical care patients, 17 of them

Zhang has already sent 17 people away.

For the first time in more than 30 years, Zhang Naofu, the deputy director of the Guangzhou Medical University, was surrounded by a deep sense of powerlessness. On Feb. 17, during a video-link consultation with academician Zhong Nanshan, the head of Zhong Nanshan's team in Wuhan, expressed frustration. "We really have tried, but so far we don't seem to see obvious results, " he said.

The 20 most vulnerable people in Wuhan lie in the Intensive Care Unit (ICU) of Xiehe West Hospital in Wuhan, which was taken over by Zhang's team. The most mild cases are fully intubated, as if they were hooked up to a breathing machine, a tube in the femoral vein at the base of the thigh that filters the blood and feeds it only with a nutrient solution. In the two weeks since taking over the ICU on Feb. 3,17 of the 36 critical care patients had left.

Every evening, he reported to Zhong Nanshan about his patients that day, and video consultations were held once a week, picking out two or three typical cases and discussing them with Guangzhou experts. On Feb. 17, as the disease dragged on, the video link mentions for the first time that a patient, called "unintubated, " is expected to be unintubated in three to four days.

Compared with SARS in 2003, NCP attacks not only the lungs, but also the heart and kidneys. Myocardial damage is particularly common in critically ill patients. He was breathing, his vitals were stable, he passed 93% of the Oxygenation, but shortly thereafter, he went into cardiac arrest.

Was the lack of oxygen for too long, or was the COVID-19 attacking the heart? Though the specialty of smoking medicine ranks first in China for many years, Zhang Nuofu can not answer this question because there are so many unknown diseases.

On the fourth floor of the ICU ward at Concord West Hospital, the original Thoracic Surgery Ward was taken over by the First Affiliated Hospital team of the National Sun Yat-sen University and also converted into an intensive care ward. The oldest of the 50 patients, 83, had just had three heart stents installed at the end of November, had kidney failure requiring years of dialysis, and had been diagnosed with lymphoma.

After the patient gets new coronary pneumonia, the oxygen exchange function of the lung becomes bad, oxygen is insufficient, affect other viscera. And the condition of other viscera worsens, can let lung damage again, complex circumstance makes treatment difficulty increases steeply. The vast majority of deaths are not simply a matter of new pneumonia.

The deputy director of the Medical Administration and Hospital Authority of the National Health Commission, Jiao Yahui, said earlier that the severe cases in Wuhan account for about 18% of all confirmed cases and in-patient cases. Their common characteristics are relatively old age and a combination of underlying diseases, the time from onset to hospitalization is relatively long, and many patients are already in critical and critical condition at the time of admission.

Compared with SARS, the disease of new coronary pneumonia progresses more rapidly and the development of Hypoxia is obvious. From the Patchy frosted glass to the Silky "white lung" , the white color usually indicates that the lungs are invaded by inflammation, often in a day or two.

Xu Huilian, deputy chief physician of respiratory medicine at Zhongshan Hospital of Zhejiang Province, had been involved in rescuing a 60-year-old male patient who had been put on a breathing machine, but his vital signs were stable, he looked healthy and his liver and kidney functions were fine. Just when Xu Huilian thought he could save the day, she found that the patient's bed had changed.

"A day is all it takes. ". Most of the previous rescues took a long time, so you can talk to the family again and again. But in Wuhan, it all happened quickly: suddenly, the patient in front of him was the "1" in the death statistics.

2
The "suicide squad" that intubated the general ward

2

###The "suicide squad" that intubated the general ward

Liu Yongjun arrived in Wuhan on the night of February 7. Shortly after the plane landed, the team leader Zhu Qingtang and 130 team members received a "death order" : 8 before 2:30 pm, the Western hospital, 6th floor East isolation ward must "open for business. ".

The Wuhan Union Hospital, which started as the third set of designated hospitals in Wuhan, was converted on February 3rd into a designated hospital for the treatment of critically ill and critically ill patients. It and the earliest gold and Silver Pool, south-central Hospital, Lung Hospital and later Tongji Hospital in the new city hospital district, Guanggu Hospital district, seven hospitals, together built the last line of defense to treat new pneumonia. These 10 hospitals provide nearly 8,000 beds.

After the outbreak began, designated hospitals did their best to expand ICU beds. The number of ICU wards in the Golden Pool Hospital has increased from one to five on the south seventh floor, and the number of ICU beds in the lung hospital has increased from 10 to 20. The ICU is home to one of the hospital's state-of-the-art facilities, and the intensity of treatment and care is unmatched in the general ward. In the ICU of a designated hospital in Wuhan, the ratio of beds to nurses reached 1∶6, with 120 nurses assigned to 20 beds.

The number of new cases being diagnosed each day has far outpaced the rate of new wards being built since the Landslide dam was cleared of previously ill patients. The hospital opened 16 new wards and expanded from 500 to 800 beds, but patients continued to pour in.

In less than 48 hours, all 50 beds on the 6th floor of the East isolation ward were fully occupied. The treatment capacity of this one ward alone was already greater than that of the whole of Guangzhou at that time.

Some of the "top priority" patients were supposed to be in the second-floor ICU, but the 20 ICU beds were already full. At least 10% of the more than 800 patients in the hospital were critically ill and needed to be intubated in the ICU. On February 13, Ma Xiaowei, director of the National Health Commission, went to the Western Union hospital to discuss with experts what measures could be taken to reduce the case fatality rate.

"Invasive Catheterization in the general ward is the only way, " Zhang replied.

The negative pressure room in the ICU keeps the air in and out of the room, as if it were breathing fresh air, but the air in the room does not escape, making sure that the virus does not contaminate the outside world, special gas treatment facilities are also provided in the wards to handle the virus-containing gases emitted by the patients. But the general ward does not have this kind of condition, soaks in the high density virus air the longer, the infection risk is higher. Anesthesiologists have never experienced anything like this before.

Ling Chumian, a anesthesiologist at the hospital, and a dozen colleagues have formed a "intubation team" to intubate the 16 isolation wards. Some people say that the "intubation squad" is not so tragic as to call it the "kamikaze" -- as if at the very moment of intubation, the patient's airways spew a powerful aerosol. Each "intubation team" consists of two anesthesiologists, one with a cowl to intubate and one with medication and assistance.

In addition to protective clothing, protective clothing and goggles, positive pressure protective headgear is standard for high-risk operations. "positive pressure" means that the pressure inside the hood is greater than the pressure outside the hood and the air outside the hood can not enter the hood. In addition, the hood is equipped with a fresh air filtration system. In the ICU ward on the 2nd floor, the first 5 positive pressure balaclavas were sent from Guangzhou by all means.

3
Lack of oxygen, equipment

3

###Lack of oxygen, equipment

The medical team with full combat effectiveness arrived in Wuhan, at first even 80% of the success can not be played. "everything you see in a hospital is divided into two steps, and the manpower is doubled, " said Chen Zhenguang, vice president of the East Side Hospital of Zhongshan's No. 1 Hospital.

In this case, from the doctor's orders to the need to replace a small wire ring on the suction machine, all the sounds converged on the intercom like a war room. All the papers in the Infectious Disease Ward may carry the virus. The doctor writes down the patient's condition and treatment advice on paper and sends it to the doctor in the clean area through a special walkie-talkie and a mobile phone, the treatment is then sent to the contaminated area, where it is administered by a doctor.

Critically ill patients face the first problem is respiratory failure, to critically ill patients with oxygen, to ensure that the patient's oxygen saturation reached a certain value, reduce the burden on the lungs, to help patients survive the most difficult time, is the critical care of critical care of the basic path.

However, the supply of oxygen was once a big problem in Wuhan. Breathing machines need oxygen to drive, oxygen is not enough, the hospital can not put in more breathing machines to treat critically ill patients. Take high flow oxygen inhalation, for example, which requires a concentration of 50 litres per minute, 10 times higher than normal. Whenever there are 4 people in the ward at the same time breathing oxygen, Liu Yongjun obviously feel oxygen pressure can not keep up with the requirements of breathing machine.

The East Hospital of People's Hospital of Wuhan University was troubled by this problem. Two critically ill patients aged nearly 80 years in the ward were seriously ill, but the oxygen supply was insufficient at that time, unable to pass through high-flow oxygen or non-invasive suction machine, and finally died.

Wuhan's Third Hospital, Guanggu district, temporarily transferred 200 oxygen cylinders from Wuhan Iron and steel, and medical workers in protective clothing carried them upstairs one by one. This simple and crude method saved many lives.

In order to ensure the supply of medical oxygen, Wuhan's main medical oxygen suppliers began to stop production. One supplier says production is four to five times what it used to be, but it's not enough.

He estimates that there are 4,000 to 5,000 breaches in Wuhan alone.

Oxygen therapy generally can be divided into four methods: Nasal high-flow oxygen, non-invasive breathing oxygen and invasive intubation, for dying patients, can be used artificial lung (ECMO) rescue, according to the patient's actual situation, step by step.

ECMO, which AIDS breathing and blood circulation, is also known as life support technology and is considered the "ultimate weapon" in the intensive care unit. However, there are only about 400 ecmos in China, and the supply of raw materials for disposable consumables is limited.

For most hospitals, ECMO is a losing proposition. In Guangdong Province, for example, ECMO costs about 50,000 yuan to start up, 130 yuan per hour to use, and nearly 100,000 yuan per week. In addition, the cost is relatively high -- a patient using ECMO requires close monitoring by multiple health care providers, and the cost of a hospital's labor is high, with an ECMO costing more than $1 million and high depreciation costs.

At present, according to the demand put forward by Hubei Province, the material support group of the Central Guidance Group is urgently looking for the source of goods in the world. More than 50 ECMOS have been initially implemented and have arrived in Wuhan one after another. They have been allocated to the Tongji Hospital, Xiehe Hospital and other designated hospitals for severe diseases.

4
Every patient needs to be treated individually

4

###Every patient needs to be treated individually

Five days do not get up, to Wuhan University People's Hospital aspiration physician Yu Changping is never the matter. He was in the ICU for the first time that day, suffocating and breathing more and more rapidly, wondering: Am I going to die?

Yu Changping is a member of the Expert Group on the prevention and treatment of new pneumonia in the hospital. He has been dealing with patients since the end of December. He has his own judgment on the condition of the patients, i had to "get through" the most dangerous two weeks. The I.C.U. is basically trying to prevent patients from dying from lack of oxygen, buy them time to get their defense systems back up and clear the virus.

Like many physicians, Yu refuses invasive intubation. After intubation, the airway "door wide open" , the original barrier filtering function disappeared, may face bacterial, fungal infection, loss of consciousness will lose their decision-making power of the disease, face more risks.

Invasive intubation is a controversial procedure among doctors. On February 13, Ma Xiaowei went to Tongji hospital to investigate the sino-french new city hospital area, also found this problem. The hospital had a case fatality rate of 5 per cent for critically ill patients, and patients were not intubated before being transferred to the ICU for long periods of non-invasive or high-flow ventilation; the medical teams had not yet fully agreed on the best time to intubate. In accordance with the protocol, whether it is high-flow oxygen or non-invasive ventilation, if 1-2 hours no significant improvement in the condition, it should be intubated.

Thinking of his good health, optimistic state of mind, Yu Changping decided to gamble: continue to use high-flow oxygen. Barely holding on, three weeks later, on the afternoon of Feb. 13, Yu withdrew his oxygen.

As the immune system fights the virus, it produces inflammatory factors. The degree of inflammation varies from person to person, and in some cases it becomes an "inflammatory storm, " like a waterfall. At first the water flows very little, and then it becomes a waterfall, only through hemodialysis, plasma exchange and other means to the inflammatory factors dialysis out of the body. Some people, they just don't make it.

Young people aren't always Python.

At present, the number of patients in their 30s and 40s who die is not small. They do not have underlying diseases and can also suffer from systemic organ failure. Li Wenliang, an ophthalmologist at Wuhan Central Hospital, was 34 when he died on February 7, and Peng Yinhua and Xia Si, two weeks later, were both 29.

Severe "sudden deterioration" , in addition to the treatment is not timely, but may also be due to inappropriate treatment, including hormone-induced secondary infection to death. The Li Ka Shing Faculty of Medicine at Li Ka Shing Medical College, the use of hormones seems to have an immediate effect, reducing inflammation, suppressing cytokine storms, treating the symptoms rather than the underlying causes, and sending the virus soaring.

For doctors, even if it seems like the same disease, the same age, but each patient's situation is different, personalized treatment is important. "With so many critical care specialists, we are aiming at the requirements of the country to reduce the death rate, so every patient needs individualized treatment, support for his organ function, support for his immune function, and treatment in all aspects, so it is possible to win this battle, " said Tang Ziren, deputy director of the Emergency Department of Beijing Chaoyang Hospital.

5
"Fish People. "

5

###"Fish People. "

In mid to early February, Zheng Xia, a doctor from Zhejiang Province who was supported in the ICU ward of Jinyintan Hospital, made a trip to the county hospital to assess critically ill patients who were suitable for transfer treatment. He visited eight hospitals and all the wards were saturated. At Wugang No. 2 Hospital, a young ICU doctor who had come from Tianjin almost begged her to leave her number in order to send a patient message. He kept repeating, "this guy's so young. He should have a chance. ".

In Wuhan, ICU beds are the most in short supply. An average of 9.84 days is required for a critically ill patient to be admitted to hospital. Early mild patients if the condition deteriorated, not timely oxygen therapy, will become serious. In many communities, delays in transferring patients to the ICU at the end of their lives often leave doctors powerless.

Zheng Xia is not the only one to "fish people" from various hospitals. Experts from the critical care inspection team of the National Health Commission were divided into 12 groups, and local experts from Wuhan were deployed to patrol the ICU wards of each designated hospital in different districts every day to assess patients with mild illnesses and screen out patients with severe illnesses, he was transferred to a designated hospital for critical and critical care.

Tong Zhaohui, a member of the Central Committee's Expert Group and Deputy Director of Beijing Chaoyang Hospital, went to the "Shelter Hospital" in Kong Hon to "scoop up people" . From the list provided by the Shelter Hospital, Tong eventually selected more than 20 people over the age of 60, with underlying diseases and requiring oxygen, and transferred them to intensive and critical care hospitals.

As of 19 February, 145 critically ill patients had been discharged from the hospital under the joint care of the Union Hospital and 11 medical teams throughout the country. Most of these patients were hospitalized around New Year's eve and recovered after more than 20 days of treatment. On February 25, two more critically ill patients were successfully extubated in the ICU ward headed by Zhang Nuofu. At present, 7 patients were extubated from suction machines.

Hospitals have seen too many deaths, with critical patients dying suddenly every day, and the number of patients being treated and discharged continues to grow. On February 23,11 more patients with severe new coronary pneumonia were discharged from Tongji hospital.

The 47-year-old critically ill patient, Chen Xinian, spent 20 days in the Union Medical College Hospital and did not know what the "lifesaver" looked like until he was discharged. He wrote three two-page thank-you letters and wrote the names of doctors and nurses in the palm of his hand, i owe my life to the state. At 3 p.m. on Feb. 19, Chen, clutching a face mask and other supplies, said he wanted to give back to society for the rest of his life.

He was discharged at the same time of serious patients, 74-year-old but optimistic strong Old Lady, but also from the hospital has been coughing up blood 44-year-old man. The scene 8 ambulances, 4 taxis, will discharge the patient to the isolation observation hotel.

On the day of his arrival at the Xihe Hospital in Wuhan, Tang Ziren realized that it was not only the patient's body that needed to be healed, but that it was as important to pass on warmth as to cure it. When the patient is isolated, the patient will be very frightened, the medical staff rounds the room to talk more, pacifies the patient mood, the psychological state is stable, the body's immune function will also be better.

On the 6th floor of the East Ward, the aunt in room 12 had just had Coronary stent surgery at the end of November. Her relatives, who were studying medicine, told her that once the new pneumonia was combined with other diseases, the course of the disease changed quickly and the recovery was poor. Every day during rounds, she pestered Liu Yongjun for more than half an hour. Every day, Liu and his colleagues tried to soothe her anxiety. Now, she's calmed down, she's obviously better, she's off her oxygen, and the CT's showing signs of improvement.

Qiu Haibo, a member of the Expert Group of the National Health Commission, said in an interview with CCTV on Feb. 25 that as of that day, there were nearly 1,000 empty beds in 10 hospitals in Wuhan designated for treatment of severe diseases, which had reached the state of "beds and other people. ".

(Yang Fang is an alias.)
